Q: Next.JS 15: &quot;await cookies()&quot; in server component called from client causes hanging A: <p>This is a known issue in Next.js 15 related to Server Actions and cookie caching. When you use <code>await cookies()</code> in multiple server actions, there can be race conditions and deadlocks due to how Next.js 15 handles the cookie store internally.</p>
<p>In Next.js 15, <code>cookies()</code> returns a <code>Promise&lt;ReadonlyRequestCookies&gt;</code> instead of just <code>ReadonlyRequestCookies</code>. The first <code>await cookies()</code> works, but subsequent calls can hang because of internal Promise resolution conflicts.</p>
<h2>Solutions</h2>
<h3>Solution 1: <strong>Pass Cookies as Parameters</strong> (Recommended)</h3>
<p>Pass the cookies from the component/server action that initially calls it:</p>
<pre><code>// actions.ts
&quot;use server&quot;

export async function getRole(cookieStore?: { get: (name: string) =&gt; { value: string } | undefined }) {
  // If cookieStore is provided, use it
  if (cookieStore) {
    return cookieStore.get(&quot;role&quot;)?.value;
  }

  // Otherwise, await cookies() (first call only)
  const store = await cookies();
  return store.get(&quot;role&quot;)?.value;
}

// OR better: make it accept the cookie value directly
export async function getUserRole(roleCookie?: string) {
  if (roleCookie) return roleCookie;

  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  return cookieStore.get(&quot;role&quot;)?.value;
}
</code></pre>

Q: Detecting Google Chrome Translation A: <p>As of 2019 the selected answer above doesn't seem to entirely work, however I have been able to use the following modified version to track the class name changes to the <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> element (<code>document.documentElement</code>) when translate or &quot;Show Original&quot; is used:</p>
<pre><code>var observer = new MutationObserver(function (event) {
    if(document.documentElement.className.includes('translated')) {
        alert(&quot;Page translate&quot;);
    } else {
        alert(&quot;Page untranslate&quot;);
    }
});

observer.observe(document.documentElement, {
  attributes: true,
  attributeFilter: ['class'],
  childList: false,
  characterData: false
});
</code></pre>
<p>However it's important to note that this will trigger at the beginning of page translation, before the individual content has actually been changed.</p>
<p>If you need to perform an action which depends on the characteristics of the translated text (e.g. to check if it now overflows a div), then you would need to track changes on elements with text content to see if they have actually been translated, while also using the above code to set a flag to determine whether the change is a result of a translation, or a reversion to the original text.</p>

Q: Can you read the footer of a workbook without opening it? A: <p>In a comment I suggested a one-line command should be able to work for different cases, but ALL office files are compressed and thus a text search requires you extract a file section of the zip and scan the decompressed text.xml.</p>
<pre><code>for /r %f in (*.xlsx) do @tar -xf &quot;%f&quot; xl/worksheets/sheet1.xml &gt;nul 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;&amp; find &quot;sharepoint&quot; xl\worksheets\sheet1.xml &gt;nul &amp;&amp; echo %~nxf is in-house &amp;&amp; del xl\worksheets\sheet1.xml &gt;nul
</code></pre>
<p>To make that more versatile for multiple files at high speed. I now suggest a batch file may be easier to modify for different situations such as xlsx or docx. After several test runs on my own examples I propose, start with:</p>
<pre><code>@echo off
setlocal enabledelayedexpansion

set &quot;topDir=C:\test&quot;
cd /d %topDir%

set &quot;extX=xlsx&quot;
set &quot;xFiles=xl/worksheets/sheet*.xml&quot;

set &quot;target=yourcompany.sharepoint.com&quot;
set &quot;report=SPmatches.txt&quot;

if exist &quot;%report%&quot; copy /y &quot;%report%&quot; &quot;%report%.backup&quot; &gt;nul 2&gt;&amp;1
echo Seeking candidate %target%, Parsing %extX% in folders starting at %topDir%, this may take a while ... 
echo Seeking candidate %target% at %DATE% %TIME% &gt;%report% &amp; echo/ &gt;&gt; %report%

set &quot;Files=%xFiles:/=\%&quot;
for /R &quot;%topDir%&quot; %%F in (*.%extX%) do (
&lt;nul set /p=.
REM Extract any candidates
 tar -xf &quot;%%F&quot; -C &quot;%TEMP%&quot; %xFiles% &gt;nul 2&gt;&amp;1
 for %%S in (&quot;%TEMP%\%Files%&quot;) do (
  find /I &quot;%target%&quot; &quot;%%S&quot; &gt;nul 2&gt;&amp;1
  if !errorlevel! EQU 0 (echo %%~fF ^(found in %%~nS^) &gt;&gt;%report%)
  del /f /q &quot;%%S&quot;
 )
)

echo Done, matches saved to %report%
pause
</code></pre>
<p>NOTE: if altering for Word.DocX the script can be easily changed to</p>
<pre><code>set &quot;xFiles=word/footer*.xml&quot;
</code></pre>
<p>or depending on in house template structure:</p>
<pre><code>set &quot;xFiles=word/document.xml&quot;
or
set &quot;xFiles=word/settings.xml&quot;
</code></pre>

