Q: API response is in stream. How should I convert that in dart so I can show it in the UI? A: <p>Actually you're correctly decoding the streamed response, but the issue is that the openapi-style streaming API does <strong>not</strong> return clean linebyline text. The <code>http</code> package stream often emits <strong>partial chunks</strong>, not full lines, so your <code>await for (final line in stream)</code> never receives a complete <code>&quot;agent-stream-start:&quot;</code> prefix to match.</p>
<p>This is why your <code>cleaned</code> value never prints.<br />
The chunk boundary may split like this:</p>
<pre><code>agent-strea
m-start:Hello, Faseeh...
</code></pre>
<p>Your replace logic never matches the whole pattern.</p>
<hr />
<h2><strong>Fix: Use a buffer and extract the prefix safely</strong></h2>
<pre><code>final stream = streamedResponse.stream.transform(utf8.decoder);

String buffer = '';

await for (final chunk in stream) {
  buffer += chunk;

  // Check if the prefix exists in the current aggregated buffer
  const prefix = &quot;agent-stream-start:&quot;;

  if (buffer.contains(prefix)) {
    final startIndex = buffer.indexOf(prefix) + prefix.length;
    final cleaned = buffer.substring(startIndex).trim();

    // Now cleaned contains your actual AI response text
    yield cleaned;

  }
}
</code></pre>
<h3>Why this works</h3>
<ol>
<li><p><strong>Stream chunks are unpredictable</strong>, so you accumulate them into a buffer.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Once the buffer contains the prefix, you safely extract everything after it.</p>
</li>
<li><p>This works even if the prefix spans multiple TCP chunks.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2><strong>If you want token-by-token UI streaming (typing effect)</strong></h2>
<pre><code>if (cleaned.isNotEmpty) {
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; cleaned.length; i++) {
    yield cleaned.substring(0, i + 1);
    await Future.delayed(const Duration(milliseconds: 12));
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>The real issue was that your <code>line</code> variable never contained the full prefix</p>

Q: calling sync functions from async function A: <p>With Python version 3.9 and later, you can use <code>asyncio.to_thread</code> to offload blocking task to a separate thread, that is usually performing I/O operations or is CPU intensive task.</p>
<p>Based on your example</p>
<pre><code>import asyncio  # I added this


def long_running_task(task):
    result = some_synchronous_function(task)
    return result

@app.route('/&lt;task&gt;', methods=['GET'])
async def do_task(task):
    ok = await asyncio.to_thread(long_running_task(task))  # I changes this
    if ok:
        return (ok.result)
