Q: How do I allocate a Vec&lt;u8&gt; that is aligned to the size of the cache line? A: <p>You can just use <code>std::alloc::alloc</code> <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/alloc/fn.alloc.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/alloc/fn.alloc.html</a></p>
<p>So to allocate a <code>Vec&lt;u8&gt;</code> of given size and alignment you can do this:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>use std::alloc::{alloc, Layout};

fn with_capacity_and_aligned(capacity: usize, alignment: usize) -&gt; Vec&lt;u8&gt; {
    assert!(alignment.is_power_of_two());
    let size = capacity.next_power_of_two();

    let layout = Layout::from_size_align(size, alignment).unwrap();
    // Safety:
    // just doing a regular alloc
    // this should never return a null pointer unless we ran out of memory
    let ptr = unsafe { alloc(layout) };

    unsafe { Vec::from_raw_parts(ptr, size, size) }
}


fn main() {
    let x = with_capacity_and_aligned(1024, 64);
    assert!(x.len() == 1024);
    assert!(x.capacity() == 1024);
}
</code></pre>

Q: How to draw a border on top of another application&#39;s window? A: <p>This will draw an outline on a panel that can be placed over another window. It avoids using WS_EX_LAYERED because that style causes problems; instead, it uses a hollow region to allow full access to the window below. This is tested and works identically on W98 and Windows 7, so it probably works on Windows 10 (but is not tested there).</p>
<pre class="lang-c prettyprint-override"><code>#include &lt;windows.h&gt;

HWND H_panel; LRESULT CALLBACK PanelPrc(); void EdgeDraw();
int WINAPI WinMain(HINSTANCE H_inst,HINSTANCE hPrevInstance,LPSTR lpCmdLine,int nCmdShow){
  DWORD N=sizeof(WNDCLASSEX); WNDCLASSEX P; memset(&amp;P,0,N);
  P.lpszClassName=&quot;PANEL&quot;; P.lpfnWndProc=PanelPrc; P.hInstance=H_inst;
  P.hCursor=LoadCursor(NULL,IDC_ARROW); P.cbSize=N;
  P.hbrBackground=GetStockObject(NULL_BRUSH);
  if(!RegisterClassEx(&amp;P)){return 0;}

  RECT R; GetWindowRect(GetDesktopWindow(),&amp;R); N=WS_EX_TOOLWINDOW|WS_EX_TOPMOST;
  H_panel=CreateWindowEx(N,P.lpszClassName,&quot;&quot;,WS_POPUP,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,H_inst,NULL);

  HRGN O=CreateRectRgnIndirect(&amp;R),I=CreateRectRgn(R.left+2,R.top+2,R.right-2,R.bottom-2);
  CombineRgn(O,O,I,RGN_DIFF); SetWindowRgn(H_panel,O,1);

  ShowWindow(H_panel,SW_SHOWNOACTIVATE);


  MSG M; while(GetMessage(&amp;M,NULL,0,0)&gt;0){TranslateMessage(&amp;M); DispatchMessage(&amp;M);}
  return M.wParam;
}

LRESULT CALLBACK PanelPrc(HWND hwnd,UINT msg,WPARAM wParam,LPARAM lParam){
  switch(msg){
    case WM_PAINT:{EdgeDraw(H_panel); return 0;} break;
    case WM_DESTROY:{PostQuitMessage(0);} break;
    default: return DefWindowProc(hwnd,msg,wParam,lParam);
  }
  return 0;
}

void EdgeDraw(HWND H){
  RECT R; HPEN P=CreatePen(0,2,0xFF00FF); int X,Y,N,O=0;
  HDC D=GetWindowDC(H); P=SelectObject(D,P);
  GetWindowRect(H,&amp;R); X=R.right-R.left,Y=R.bottom-R.top;
  int C[4][2]={{O+1,O+1},{O+1,O+Y-1},{O+X-1,O+Y-1},{O+X-1,O+1}};
  MoveToEx(D,O+1,O+1,NULL); N=4; while(N--){LineTo(D,C[N][0],C[N][1]);}
  P=SelectObject(D,P); DeleteObject(P); ReleaseDC(H,D);
}
</code></pre>
<p>This example is complete because it's important to do things in the right order, and in a fully established context, if you want the result to be flicker-free at all times.</p>
<p>There is a compromise: The region must be set to allow some area(s) to allow through-clicks, or to be drawn on. It can't do both. This is a limitation of the basic API functions used, being chosen for widest compatibility. If someone knows a way to improve on this without sacrificing that, go for it...</p>
<p>Reasons to avoid WS_EX_LAYERED:</p>
<p>It's not part of the original API, so could never be consistent across all Windows variants. It forces the task bar/switcher windows to have entries for the hidden window, and prevents it from showing normally in Windows 7 (though it will still appear in W98, and even there, the task entries exist when not wanted if WS_EX_LAYERED is set). Also, in Windows 7, if the drawn outline intercepts the taskbar, unrest results. It's ugly. Avoiding WS_EX_LAYERED is far easier than trying to manage its consequences.</p>

Q: Tic Tac Toe in Google Sheets (Apps Script) A: <p>This should help, it will check if the range is in the first three columns and rows, and then set the value to X or O and change the turn. Instead of working with getting the SpreadsheetApp, I used the e from onEdit(e) which gives you a more direct path to the selected area and its value. </p>

<pre><code>//Set board between a specific range. 

function onEdit(e) {
  if(e){
  var ss = SpreadsheetApp.getActive();
  var range = e.range;

  //Check that its in the begining range
  if(range.getColumn() &lt; 4 &amp;&amp; range.getRow() &lt; 4) {
    //Get the turn
    var turnRange = ss.getRange("J2");
    var turn = turnRange.getValue();

    //If the checkbox is checked
    if(range.getValue() == true){
      if(turn == 'X') {
        //set the box to X and change turn to O
        range.setValue("X");
        turnRange.setValue("O");
      }else if(turn == 'O'){
        //Set box to O and change turn to X
        range.setValue("O"); 
        turnRange.setValue("X");
      }
    }
    }
   }
}
</code></pre>

